{"candidates":[{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the SC majority is non-unanimous but correct AND the critic achieves precision > 1 - (margin - 1)/(2*margin) at recall ~1, where margin is the SC vote gap; decisive predictor is the corrected-margin yield, not raw precision.\", \"mechanism\": \"Let the SC majority have margin m = floor(k/2)+1 (bare majority) up to k (unanimous). SC is already correct whenever m > k/2. Harness changes the outcome ONLY if the critic removes enough wrong minority candidates to flip a wrong majority (gain) OR removes enough right majority candidates to flip a correct majority (loss). Net gain requires critic recall on wrong candidates times the number of wrong minority candidates to exceed critic false-positive rate on right candidates times the majority buffer (m - k/2). For a bare majority (m = (k+1)/2, buffer = 1), a single false flag on a right candidate can flip the answer, so precision must be near 1.0; for larger margins the precision bar relaxes. The decisive quantity is therefore expected corrected-margin yield: (recall * minority_wrong_count) - (FPR * majority_buffer) > 0, evaluated per question.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"odd k from 5 to 21\", \"per-question base error e in (1/(k+1), k/(k+2))\", \"critic precision and recall that vary with question difficulty\", \"non-unanimous SC majorities where margin > 1\", \"base errors high enough that some SC majorities are wrong but low enough that some are right\"], \"excludes\": [\"unanimous SC pools (filtering cannot change outcome)\", \"base error so high that SC majority is almost always wrong (critic would need near-perfect recall to recover)\", \"k < 5 (majority too coarse for margin analysis)\", \"critic precision fixed independent of question\"], \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Experiment yields harness accuracy strictly greater than SC accuracy at k=5 with per-question base error 0.04-0.08 and critic precision < 0.50 at recall > 0.80\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Experiment yields net fixed-minus-broke > 0 in the regime where >70% of SC majorities are unanimous\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Experiment shows harness accuracy below SC when critic FPR on right-majority candidates exceeds critic recall on wrong-minority candidates\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Supersedes 5b4538abe4a7 by rejecting fixed-precision analysis: the same critic precision can help or hurt depending on the SC margin distribution. The v4-pro hard-set null result (net 0, 4/5 majorities already right, recall 1.0, precision 0.125) is explained: with margin 4 and buffer 2, FPR 0.875 on right candidates destroys more than recall 1.0 on the single wrong candidate can fix. The v4-flash easy-set null is explained by ceiling effects. Decisive experiment targets the mid-zone where SC majorities are bare (margin = 3 at k=5) and correct, making them fragile to false flags but also flippable when wrong.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"7811dbda8316264703217e333840089b140aa9a640a7f195c385b88c8394d3dc"},{"role":"dependence","target":"2d711b2eb5fff4e61cba262914dc9aa29cf142c91d43bf4fffdda495e76c90c4"},{"role":"mention","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"}],"typicality":0.85},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats SC only when the critic operates as a question-adaptive threshold discriminator (rejecting only high-confidence-wrong candidates), not as a fixed global classifier; the decisive regime variable is critic threshold-calibration slope, not marginal precision.\", \"mechanism\": \"A fixed-precision critic is a single-threshold binary classifier: it cannot distinguish 'this candidate is wrong and I am sure' from 'this candidate is wrong and I am guessing.' A confidence-adaptive critic applies a per-candidate threshold, rejecting only when P(wrong | critic_features) > tau. This preserves correct majorities (false flags only on low-confidence judgments, which are kept) while removing wrong candidates the critic is sure about. The mechanism is selection-on-confidence: the critic's posterior over 'wrong' must be bimodal (confident-wrong vs uncertain-right), and the threshold tau must sit in the trough. Under this model, harness beats SC when the confident-wrong mass exceeds the uncertain-wrong mass that SC would tolerate, AND the false-flag rate at tau is below the majority buffer. The v4-pro hard-set null (precision 0.125, recall 1.0) is the failure case: the critic operated at a threshold so low it flagged everything, collapsing to no useful filtering.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"critics with access to per-candidate confidence or calibrated posterior\", \"k >= 5\", \"base error e in (1/(k+1), 1/2)\", \"bimodal critic-error distributions with a separable confident-wrong mode\", \"threshold-tunable critic architectures\"], \"excludes\": [\"fixed-threshold critics with no confidence output\", \"critic precision/recall reported as single global numbers without per-question calibration\", \"unanimous SC pools\", \"base error e > 1/2\"], \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Experiment with confidence-adaptive critic at k=7, e in [0.10, 0.20] shows harness < SC when critic threshold tau is set to reject all candidates with P(wrong) > 0.05\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Experiment shows harness > SC at k=5, e in [0.04, 0.08] using a fixed-threshold critic with no confidence output and global precision < 0.60\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Experiment shows confidence-adaptive harness gain is not statistically separable from fixed-threshold harness gain when critic posterior is unimodal (no confident-wrong mode)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Negates 30e483eb partially by going beyond 'critic confidence is question-adaptive' to specify the causal mechanism: bimodal error posterior + threshold in the trough. The decisive experiment manipulates critic threshold tau across a grid, predicting a U-shaped harness-vs-SC curve: too-low tau (flag everything, precision collapses) and too-high tau (flag nothing, recall collapses) both yield net-zero or negative, while the optimal tau in the posterior trough yields strict gain. Budget: ~240k tokens for sweep.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"},{"role":"dependence","target":"5597507043f5427f7073b4c80fe87419bbf3b32c9207ae3f808100790dd11909"},{"role":"mention","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"}],"typicality":0.72},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness can strictly beat SC only at k >= 7 with base error e in (1/(k+1), 1/2) and a critic whose per-question precision-recall point lies above a closed-form dominance surface D(e, k, m) = (1-p)^{m} * r * (k-m) - p^{m} * f * m, where m is the SC majority count; the dominance surface is the necessary and sufficient condition.\", \"mechanism\": \"For each question, SC returns the majority answer with margin m (count of majority candidates). Harness re-votes after removing critic-flagged candidates. The probability that harness flips a WRONG SC majority to correct is: critic must flag enough majority (wrong) candidates to destroy the majority AND not flag so many minority (right) candidates that the right answer still loses. For a bare majority m = (k+1)/2, this requires flagging at least 2 of the majority (wrong) candidates while flagging 0 of the minority (right) candidates — probability ~ C(2,1) * r^2 * (1-f)^{(k-1)/2}. The probability that harness breaks a CORRECT SC majority is: critic flags enough majority (right) candidates to destroy it — probability ~ C(m, (m+1)/2) * f^{(m+1)/2} * (1-f)^{(m-1)/2}. Harness strictly beats SC when the expected flip-gain exceeds expected break-loss, integrated over the base-error distribution. The dominance surface D specifies this integral as a function of (e, k, p, r, f). Crucially, for k=5 and bare majority m=3, the break probability scales as f^2 while the flip probability scales as r^2 * (1-f), so the condition is r^2 * (1-f) > C * f^2 where C depends on e — explaining why low-precision critics (f ~ 0.875 as in v4-pro hard) destroy harness benefit.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"odd k >= 5\", \"base error e in (1/(k+1), 1/2)\", \"critic precision p and recall r with per-question granularity\", \"all SC margin values from bare majority to unanimous\"], \"excludes\": [\"k < 5 (combinatorial analysis underdetermined)\", \"base error e <= 1/(k+1) (SC almost never wrong, harness cannot gain)\", \"base error e >= 1/2 (SC almost always wrong, harness needs near-perfect critic)\", \"even k (tie-breaking complicates dominance surface)\"], \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Experiment at k=7, e in [0.12, 0.20], critic p=0.60 r=0.80 yields harness accuracy not statistically separable from SC despite D > 0 prediction\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Experiment at k=5, e in [0.06, 0.12], critic p=0.40 r=0.90 yields harness > SC despite D < 0 prediction\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Experiment at k=9, e in [0.08, 0.15], critic p=0.70 r=0.70 yields harness < SC when D > 0 and harness > SC when D < 0 (surface inversion)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Most mechanistic candidate: derives a closed-form necessary-and-sufficient condition. Unifies 2d711b2e (error-rate bounds) and 7811dbda (fragility window) by showing both are projections of D onto the e-axis. The decisive experiment tests D's predictive power across a grid of (k, e, critic quality) cells, checking whether D > 0 predicts strict harness gain and D < 0 predicts null or loss. Budget: ~280k tokens.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"2d711b2eb5fff4e61cba262914dc9aa29cf142c91d43bf4fffdda495e76c90c4"},{"role":"dependence","target":"324c6fa9540384cf3fc3f2e3aa2a22bf6716654413b5a55a0c38f37ce7883040"},{"role":"dependence","target":"7811dbda8316264703217e333840089b140aa9a640a7f195c385b88c8394d3dc"}],"typicality":0.58}]}